  "text": "where a is a vector of unit length and a T a = 1. a T x 1 and a T x 2 are the orthogonal projections of the vectors x 1 and x 2 on the linear space spanned by a, respectively. S is the covariance matrix of x 1 and x 2 . Thus, f (a) denotes the univariate standard distance between vectors x 1 and x 2 in the one-dimensional subspace spanned by a. According to [CITATION_1] , the multivariate standard distance between x 1 and x 2 is attained for a = c(x 1 − x 2 ) T S −1 (x 1 − x 2 ) and takes the value: In this study, fault detection is carried out using a new health index T c that combines Hotelling's T 2 and Q statistics and the CVR-based monitoring index T d .",
